          "title": "Jeconiah the prisoner — the dynasty's nadir and God's fidelity",
          "body": "The phrase 'Jeconiah the prisoner' (*assir*) at 3:17 is the chapter's single most freighted epithet. Jehoiachin was taken captive to Babylon in 597 BC, and Jeremiah had pronounced a devastating oracle over him: 'Write this man down as childless... for no man of his descendants will prosper sitting on the throne of David' (Jeremiah 22:30). Read superficially, this appears to end the royal line. The Chronicler's response is to list Jeconiah's sons — Shealtiel, Malchiram, Pedaiah, and four more (3:17-18) — without comment, without apology. The argument is structural: yes, no son of his will sit on David's *throne* (Jeremiah's word is about the throne, not the bloodline), but the biological line continues. Matthew's genealogy (Matthew 1:11-12) will run through Jeconiah, resolving the Jeremiah tension through the virgin birth: Jesus is the legal heir through Joseph (Davidic through Solomon, through Jeconiah) but not biologically descended from Jeconiah's cursed male line — He is biologically descended through Mary (whose Davidic descent through Nathan is the subject of Luke 3). The Chronicler could not have seen all of this, but he kept listing names."
