          "title": "The chapter's forward horizon — toward Messiah",
          "body": "1 Chronicles 3 ends not with a king, not with a temple-builder, but with seven obscure sons of Elioenai (3:24) — names that appear nowhere else in canonical Scripture and whose historical fate is unknown. This is the point. The Davidic line has been reduced from palace to obscurity, from throne to private household. Yet the Chronicler lists it. The implication for the post-exilic community — and, read canonically, for every reader after — is that the biological thread continues in the hands of God even when the political structure that once displayed it has collapsed entirely. Matthew 1:1-17 is the chapter's New Testament commentary: from Abraham through David through Solomon through Jeconiah through Zerubbabel, the line reaches 'Joseph the husband of Mary, by whom Jesus was born, who is called the Messiah' (Matthew 1:16). The chapter's final word is not seven obscure names — it is the one name all of those names were carrying without knowing it."
