        "body": "The chapter opens with a domestic catalogue that modern readers pass quickly and ancient readers studied carefully. Nineteen sons are named — six in Hebron, thirteen in Jerusalem — by seven named women plus unnamed concubines. The political complexity of David's household is laid bare without editorial comment. Ahinoam the Jezreelitess, Abigail the Carmelitess, Maacah the Geshurite princess, Haggith, Abital, Eglah, and Bathsheba (Bath-shua) — the mothers come from Israelite commoners, foreign royalty, and the most scandalous union in the royal record. The Chronicler includes them all without apology or moralizing.\n\nThe geographic structure of the list (Hebron sons first, Jerusalem sons second) carries theological weight. Hebron is the city of beginnings — Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, and the first seven years of David's reign. Jerusalem is the city of covenant culmination. Sons born in Jerusalem are born into the era of the ark's return, the temple promise, and the Davidic covenant proper (2 Samuel 7). Solomon appears as the first of four sons by Bathsheba in Jerusalem (3:5) — his positional prominence foreshadows his election as covenant successor, even though he is fourteenth in the birth order overall.\n\nThe closing verse of the panel (3:9) is a formal summary: 'All these were the sons of David, besides the sons of the concubines; and Tamar was their sister.' The Chronicler deliberately mentions Tamar by name. She appears nowhere else in Chronicles — the story of her rape by Amnon (2 Samuel 13) is never narrated in Chronicles. But the name alone carries the memory. Every reader in 450 BC who knew 2 Samuel 13 would feel the weight of that inclusion. The dynasty's founding breadth is not morally uncomplicated. God chose to work through this household.\n\nSwindoll notes, in his treatment of David's household (Great Lives: David), that the complexity of David's family was not incidental to his failures but continuous with them — the multiplication of wives that Deuteronomy 17:17 explicitly prohibited set the conditions for the rivalry, violence, and rebellion of 2 Samuel 13-20. The Chronicler does not rehearse those narratives, but his careful listing of the mothers makes clear he is aware of the household's fracture lines. The covenant did not depend on the dynasty's moral health. It depended on the covenant-maker."
