        "body": "With verse 10, the chapter shifts registers entirely. The broad household of David gives way to a strict vertical chain: one man, one son, one man, one son — nineteen iterations across five verses. The literary effect is striking. Where David's section spread horizontally across mothers and cities, Solomon's succession line is ruthlessly vertical. This is because only one line matters now — the throne line, the temple-builder line, the line through which the Davidic covenant will be institutionally expressed.\n\nThe list covers the entire monarchic period of the Judean kingdom — from Rehoboam (ca. 930 BC) through Josiah (died 609 BC), approximately 320 years. Readers who knew Kings would hear the entire history encoded in these names: the schism under Rehoboam, the revival under Asa and Jehoshaphat, the Baalism of Joram (who married Ahab's daughter), the temple repair under Joash, the pride of Amaziah, the leprosy of Azariah (Uzziah), the faithfulness of Hezekiah, the wickedness of Manasseh, and the great reformation under Josiah. The Chronicler does not narrate any of it here. The names do the work.\n\nThe theological point of this terse succession list is that God sustained the Davidic covenant through every one of these reigns without exception. When Joram killed his own brothers to secure the throne (2 Chronicles 21:4), the covenant survived. When Ahaz shut the temple doors and burned his son as an offering to Molech (2 Chronicles 28:2-3), the covenant survived. When Manasseh filled Jerusalem with innocent blood (2 Kings 21:16), the covenant survived — not because Manasseh deserved it but because God had sworn on His own name to David (2 Samuel 7:15-16; Psalm 89:30-37). Calvin, in his commentary on Chronicles, observes that the list of Judean kings is evidence of a divine patience that is nothing short of miraculous: 'God bore with them not for their sakes but for the sake of His servant David and for the sake of Jerusalem which He had chosen.'\n\nThe panel ends abruptly at Josiah (3:14). Verse 15 then pivots to list Josiah's sons individually rather than continuing the 'his son' chain — because after Josiah there is no normal succession. Four sons of Josiah are named, but only two became kings (Jehoiakim and Jehoahaz/Shallum), one was deported to Egypt before he could reign (Johanan, likely), and one (Zedekiah) was the last king before the exile. The dynasty is beginning to fracture even in the listing.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** The succession formula *ben-o* ('his son') is repeated without variation through 3:10-14 — a deliberate monotony that enacts the covenant's steadiness. The abrupt shift to 'the sons of Josiah were...' (*bene yoshiyyah*, a listing formula rather than the succession formula) at 3:15 signals a structural break. The grammar tells you the monarchy is ending before the history does."
